      "question": "In $\\triangle ABC$, a line segment $DE$ is drawn parallel to $BC$ such that $D$ lies on $AB$ and $E$ lies on $AC$. If $AD = 3 \\text{ cm}$, $DB = 2 \\text{ cm}$, and the area of $\\triangle ADE$ is $18 \\text{ cm}^2$, find the area of the quadrilateral $DBCE$.",
      "answer": "$32 \\text{ cm}^2$",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Since $DE \\parallel BC$, by Basic Proportionality Theorem, $\\triangle ADE \\sim \\triangle ABC$. The ratio of sides $\\frac{AD}{AB} = \\frac{3}{3+2} = \\frac{3}{5}$.",
          "The ratio of areas of similar triangles is the square of the ratio of corresponding sides, so $\\frac{\\text{Area}(\\triangle ADE)}{\\text{Area}(\\triangle ABC)} = (\\frac{3}{5})^2 = \\frac{9}{25}$.",
          "Calculate $\\text{Area}(\\triangle ABC) = 18 \\times \\frac{25}{9} = 50 \\text{ cm}^2$. The area of quadrilateral $DBCE = \\text{Area}(\\triangle ABC) - \\text{Area}(\\triangle ADE) = 50 - 18 = 32 \\text{ cm}^2$."
        ],
        "derivation": "$\\frac{AD}{AB} = \\frac{3}{3+2} = \\frac{3}{5} \\Rightarrow \\frac{\\text{Area}(\\triangle ADE)}{\\text{Area}(\\triangle ABC)} = (\\frac{3}{5})^2 = \\frac{9}{25} \\Rightarrow \\text{Area}(\\triangle ABC) = 18 \\times \\frac{25}{9} = 50 \\text{ cm}^2 \\Rightarrow \\text{Area}(DBCE) = 50 - 18 = 32 \\text{ cm}^2$"
      },
